{"source_key":"sha256-197fe1f25af7094b92a33a46616d8db4","record_index":258,"record_hash":"sha256:8c37470d59f5a9e75b4a6233d3debce1f64df455a63afa4faa5b3473098d3069","timestamp":"2026-05-24T14:41:55.823Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: b78240\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 2236\nOutput:\n     1\t# Agent Trail\n     2\t\n     3\tAgent Trail is the review-adjacent product surface for captured agent sessions.\n     4\tIt is the page a reviewer opens from a pull request to understand the agent work\n     5\tbehind a change.\n     6\t\n     7\t## Working Name\n     8\t\n     9\tUse **Agent Trail** for now.\n    10\t\n    11\tGood PR link text:\n    12\t\n    13\t- View Agent Trail\n    14\t- Explore Agent Trail\n    15\t- Agent Trail for this PR\n    16\t\n    17\tAvoid names like \"transcript\", \"audit log\", or \"provenance report\" for the\n    18\tproduct surface. The page may contain transcript records and provenance facts,\n    19\tbut the user-facing promise is simpler: follow the useful trail behind this\n    20\tchange.\n    21\t\n    22\t## Product Shape\n    23\t\n    24\tA developer opens a pull request from GitButler or GitHub. GitButler adds a link\n    25\tto the pull request. A reviewer clicks that link and lands on a GitButler-owned\n    26\tweb page for the Agent Trail.\n    27\t\n    28\tThe page lets the reviewer explore captured agent context related to the pull\n    29\trequest:\n    30\t\n    31\t- prompts and requests from the human\n    32\t- assistant responses and claims\n    33\t- tool calls and tool results\n    34\t- tests and validation attempts\n    35\t- decisions and tradeoffs\n    36\t- follow-up questions\n    37\t- edge cases discussed or missed\n    38\t\n    39\tThis is not primarily a chat transcript viewer. The transcript is the source of\n    40\ttruth, but the review experience should be organized around helping a reviewer\n    41\tunderstand the change.\n    42\t\n    43\t## Core Question\n    44\t\n    45\tAgent Trail should answer:\n    46\t\n    47\t> What agent context helps me review this pull request?\n    48\t\n    49\tIt should not claim:\n    50\t\n    51\t> This agent session authored this pull request.\n    52\t\n    53\tThe language should stay evidence-based. Say that a session or turn is related\n    54\tto a pull request, branch, review, or ch\n[TRUNCATED]\nthentication prompt\n   169\t- a clear \"no trail available\" state\n   170\t\n   171\tOn-demand generation is attractive because it avoids needing every PR to be\n   172\tpre-linked by GitButler. It also gives reviewers a memorable gesture: replace\n   173\tthe forge domain with the Agent Trail domain.\n   174\t\n   175\tOpen design questions:\n   176\t\n   177\t- Should generated trails be cached automatically?\n   178\t- Who can publish or persist the generated result?\n   179\t- What should happen when no captured agentlog data exists for the PR?\n   180\t- How should GitHub authentication map to GitMeta/Forge access?\n   181\t\n   182\t## Data Source\n   183\t\n   184\tAgent Trail should build on `but-agentlog` primitives:\n   185\t\n   186\t- durable project-scoped agent sessions\n   187\t- capture turns inside sessions\n   188\t- transcript records inside turns\n   189\t- observed branch, review, and change targets\n   190\t- verified related-session lookup\n   191\t- bounded turn and record hydration\n   192\t\n   193\t`but-agentlog` should remain the evidence layer. Agent Trail should live above\n   194\tit as a product-specific projection and browsing layer.\n   195\t\n   196\t## Repository And Hosting Boundary\n   197\t\n   198\tThe Agent Trail website or service should not live inside the GitButler\n   199\trepository by default.\n   200\t\n   201\tGitButler should own the local evidence plumbing:\n   202\t\n   203\t- capture\n   204\t- redaction\n   205\t- GitMeta storage and sync\n